Brief analysis of Recla data

This is a quick analysis of the data from Recla et al. (2014) and Logan et al (2013), available at https://github.com/rqtl/qtl2data/tree/master/DO_Recla

We first load the data directly from the web.

library(qtl2)
file <- paste0("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/rqtl/",
               "qtl2data/master/DO_Recla/recla.zip")
recla <- read_cross2(file)

We calculate genotype probabilities. I use n_cores <- 0 throughout (which detects the number of available CPU cores and uses all of them). If you have limited wRAM on your machine, you may need to change this to n_cores <- 1.

n_cores <- 0
probs <- calc_genoprob(recla, cores=n_cores)

We now convert the genotype probabilities to haplotype dosages.

aprobs <- genoprob_to_alleleprob(probs, cores=n_cores)

We now calculate kinship matrices, by the leave one chromosome out (loco) method.

kinship <- calc_kinship(aprobs, "loco", cores=n_cores)

A genome scan of all phenotypes.

out <- scan1(aprobs, recla$pheno, kinship, cores=n_cores)

Plot of the results, all in gray except for the trait with the largest LOD score, in blue.

plot(out, recla$gmap, lodcolumn=1, col="gray60",
     ylim=c(0, maxlod(out)*1.05))
for(i in 2:ncol(out))
    plot(out, recla$gmap, lodcolumn=i, col="gray60", add=TRUE)
plot(out, recla$gmap, lodcolumn=5, col="slateblue", add=TRUE)

Here are the peaks above 6.5.

find_peaks(out, recla$gmap, threshold=6.5)
